social_posts.post_text:
One thing about me is I am always looking for another mountain to climb, but the shadow side of that trait is that I often forget to appreciate the view from where I am right now, at this moment.
.
Seven years ago, I'd written ten books, but was beginning to lose hope that I'd ever write anything people would actually want to read. I was drowning in rejections and as positive a face as I tried to put on it, they were really getting to me. If I could go back and tell that Laura that in seven years time she would have published seven books and connected with readers around the world who found something in my stories that spoke to them, my younger self would be proud. My current self is proud too, because even if there are still mountains I want to climb, I have to admit--the view from this one is pretty damn spectacular.
.

location.city_name: Newens The Original Maids of Honour

social_posts.post_text:
The highlight of my impromptu mini break to Kew was this little bakery I stumbled upon. This location of Newens The Original Maids of Honour has been around for more than 150 years, but its legacy is even older than that--Henry VIII named their namesake tart after coming upon Anne Boleyn and other maids of honour eating a plate full of them, tried one and loved it so much he confiscated the recipe and had it locked in an iron box within nearby Richmond Palace. One account even says that he had the maid who invented the tart imprisoned on the palace's grounds so that she could produce them exclusively for Henry VIII and his court. While that may not be true, the recipe did eventually make its way to this little shop where they're still served today.
.
And as a self-proclaimed pastry aficionado, I have to say--Henry VIII had plenty of issues, but his taste in pastries was impeccable.
.

It's hard to believe it's been five years since Theodosia made her way into the world, but I'm as grateful as ever that you all let her into your hearts and followed her journey.
.
My path to getting my first book published was long and winding, and there were times I thought ASH PRINCESS might end up trunked like the nine manuscripts I wrote before it, but Theo's story of resilience, rebellion, and revenge refused to let me go.
.
What a wild five years it's been, with wild dreams come true and surreal moments I still can't believe, but the best part has been getting to connect with readers and see how you all have taken Theo and her story, made her your own, and kept her alive. It's everything I dreamed of and more. 💕🔥✨
.

One of the best bits of writing advice I ever got was actually advice from an acting teacher that I adapted slightly: you don't have to write every day to be a writer, just do something, every day, to make yourself a better writer, even if that is just living your life, seeking out inspiration and also letting it find you. Have conversations with friends, people watch, check out a new place (hi, Vauxhall, you're fab). How can we possibly write about being human if we don't let ourselves live? Sometimes I need to remind myself that I'm more than my word count, and if you need that reminder today, too, I'm happy to give it. 💛💛💛
.

"It’s time to show the empress exactly who she raised us to be."
.
“And make her regret it.”
.
The third and final book in the CASTLES IN THEIR BONES series is off to copyedits and I thought I'd share a little snippet that sums up the book perfectly. I can't believe that's a wrap on my second series, and as bittersweet as it is to close this story that has taken up the last five years of my life, I'm so excited to share it with all of you.
.
But even as their story comes to a close, Daphne, Beatriz, Sophronia, and Violie (and all their friends and foes) have taken up permanent residence in my heart. I love these messy girls dearly, and it's been such an honor to grow with them these past years, as an author and as a person, and I'll love them long after the stars go dark.
.

Sometimes I think about how weird it must be for people I've lost touch with in the real world to see me on here growing weird looking produce (intentionally!) and cooking all sorts of new dishes because until around five years ago, I was so incredibly picky and afraid of trying new things that I lived on a diet of chicken fingers, mac and cheese (shells only), and white rice with salt. Maybe broccoli if I wanted to be healthy, but only steamed with salt and butter. But while I stand by all of those as delicious, I've definitely broadened my horizons to the point where gardening and cooking have become the hobbies that keep me sane even during the most anxiety-ridden times.
.
Younger me would have wrinkled her nose at these squash (both the summer patty pan variety and the winter honeynut in progress). She would have said the only time she liked tomatoes was in ketchup. She'd have proclaimed that she hated eggplants and peppers even if the truth was she'd never even tried them. Now, though, I love it all.
.
Side note: does anyone have any patty pan recipes they'd like to share? I somehow wound up with five plants so I am going to have a LOT of over the next month or two!
.

Oh 2023.
.
I would be lying if I said you were my favorite year, but you had your bright spots and I'm more grateful for those than I can say. Here are a few of those bright spots, most of which (I think) never saw the light of day/the Instagram feed.
.
A bit of transparency--you may have noticed I've been a bit quieter on here than I usually am, but it hasn't been the best time for me mental health wise and I took a little step back to take better care of myself. I'm definitely leaving 2023 in a better place than I entered it, though, and I'm hoping to be around more in 2024. 💕
